Section B – Work and Recent Onboarding

[06:00] Interviewer: Think about the last time you started a new job or changed teams. What was your experience during the first few days?

[06:30] Participant P04: My first week was quite stressful. Everyone expected me to learn quickly, but there wasn't a clear plan. I spent a lot of time asking questions because I didn't know where information was stored or who was responsible for different tasks.

[08:40] Interviewer: During the first two weeks, what were the three most important things you needed to know?

[09:00] Participant P04: First, I needed to understand company procedures. Second, I needed to learn how to use the internal software. Third, I needed to know the responsibilities of different team members so I knew who to contact when problems happened.

[11:20] Interviewer: What was the hardest part of getting started?

[11:40] Participant P04: The hardest part was understanding different systems. Every department used different software and there wasn't one place where everything was explained. It took me several weeks before I felt comfortable.

[13:30] Interviewer: Did onboarding feel helpful or did it feel like completing a checklist?

[13:50] Participant P04: Some parts were helpful, especially meeting experienced colleagues. However, many online training modules felt like they were only there to complete mandatory requirements rather than preparing me for my actual work.

Section C – Finding Information at Work

[16:00] Interviewer: When you need an answer at work, where do you usually look first?

[16:20] Participant P04: I normally check Microsoft Teams. If I can't find the information there, I search emails, company documents and finally ask another supervisor.

[18:10] Interviewer: How often do you need to check more than one place?

[18:30] Participant P04: Almost every day. Information is spread across different systems. Sometimes I spend fifteen or twenty minutes searching before finding the latest document.

[20:20] Interviewer: Can you tell me about a time when you couldn't find something important?

[20:45] Participant P04: One day I needed an updated health and safety procedure before starting work in a warehouse area. I found three different versions of the same document. I wasn't sure which one was correct, so I had to wait until the health and safety manager confirmed the latest version.

[22:50] Interviewer: How do you personally keep track of important documents and tasks?

[23:10] Participant P04: I keep a notebook, save useful links in Microsoft Teams and set reminders on my phone. It works, but I still feel everything is spread across too many places.
